    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="background">
Harry Marks, in response to Bailar, raises useful questions about
the import of &quot;STS&quot; projects.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="34" relname="span"> Except to note that STS is very
far from monolothic, I shall conclude this preface and get
to discussion.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="4" relname="nonvolitional-cause">

1. It seems to me that the core project in STS, in all its
variants, has been to demonstrate that components of the
social order are embedded in the conclusions of science.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="20" relname="span"> This
has a variety of consequences,</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="21" relname="span"> but the central consequence
is that the conclusions of science are not independent of the
social/civil/politiccal order,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="32" relname="span"> and therefore cannot be used
as an independent means of adjudicating social/civil/political
questions -- contrary to opposing claims, made from a range of
interests, some of them successful.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="23" relname="preparation">

Some upshots:</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="9" relname="nonvolitional-cause">

a. Because the program is not monolithic,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="23" relname="list"> the message has been
mixed and therefore is too easily dismissed through obfuscation 
(in some pernicious cases) and through direct quotation (some
STS analysts are self-obfuscating).</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="24" relname="span">

b. Whether true or not, the message has been deemed a message from
the left.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="concession"> It might as easily be embraced by the (American) right,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="22" relname="span">
but apart from Creationist appropriations, it has not.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="29" relname="span">

2. There are alternative programs, the possibilities of which have
not, I think, been explored.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="27" relname="span"> I&apos;ll confine my comment to one such
alternative: developing an aesthetics of science.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="26" relname="span"> It appears to me
that a significant number of philosophers of science have mixed
their (unremarked) aesthetics with their epistemologies.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="14" relname="elaboration"> This
is both implicitly the case (which calls for some tricky analysis
to tease the aesthetic judgments from justification) and explicitly,
as in attempts to identify &quot;simplicity&quot; (a 20th century aesthetic
virtue) in the conditions for theory choice.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="28" relname="contrast">

Restated, some science may be pretty but not true;</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="28" relname="contrast"> some science may
be unpretty but true.</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="28" relname="elaboration"> One might devise a means for making this distinction.</segment>
